{"type":"message","id":"48f31ad0","parentId":"dc330d34","timestamp":"2026-03-19T15:09:57.056Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ACTIVE_TASK.md looks fine now - it's Status: done. But the user is saying that in the past, after completing one step, the system would stop and not continue to the next. This suggests that the mechanism wasn't working properly.\n\nLet me think about what could cause this:\n\n1. The ACTIVE_TASK.md is the recovery rail - but it's only read when a new message comes in\n2. After completing one step, the system should update ACTIVE_TASK.md and immediately move to the next step\n3. But if there's no follow-up trigger (user message, cron, heartbeat), the system might just go silent\n\nThe issue is likely that:\n- The \"continue from Current\" mechanism only fires when there's a continuation message from the user\n\n\n- Between steps, there's no automatic trigger unless a heartbeat or cron fires\n- The AGENTS.md rules state that on session restart or task interruption, I should recover by reading ACTIVE_TASK.md first\n- But when a multi-step task is actively running, after completing one step and updating the file, the system waits for the next message rather than automatically continuing to the next item\n\nThe core problem seems to be that even though I've been updating the file correctly after each step, the system isn't actually moving to the next step without an external trigger.\n\nI've been doing everything right according to the rules—updating ACTIVE_TASK.md, rewriting the whole file instead of partial edits, reading it back to verify state, then moving to the next item. But looking back at the execution history, the \"继续修理\" message did come in after completing the previous task, which means the continuation mechanism actually did work. However, there were other times where I finished one step, updated the file correctly, but the system didn't automatically proceed to the next step without me intervening.\n\nThe real issue is that when I'm actively executing steps within a single session turn, the system doesn't automatically move to the next item after completing one. The AGENTS.md guidance to \"immediately start the next item\" conflicts with how turns actually work—when I'm processing a message and all tool calls in a single response complete, there's no automatic trigger to pick up the next one. The system only advances when a new message arrives or an external trigger fires. I need to make sure that after each step's minimum deliverable, I both update the ACTIVE_TASK.md file and explicitly continue to the next step in my response.","thinkingSignature":"b89ec2a9782f8e67ccb265aab79a2eed8f5c8bbe0682533b97f64726d89f52d4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_i2x1x6hl1l6b_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/active_task_cli.py 2>/dev/null | head -50"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":120717,"output":535,"cacheRead":24293,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145545,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773932968824}}
{"type":"message","id":"2b1c8511","parentId":"48f31ad0","timestamp":"2026-03-19T15:09:57.111Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_i2x1x6hl1l6b_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport argparse\nimport json\nimport re\nimport sys\nimport tempfile\nfrom datetime import datetime\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nMETA_FIELDS = [\n    \"Status\",\n    \"Priority\",\n    \"Started\",\n    \"Updated\",\n    \"Workspace\",\n    \"Owner\",\n    \"User Trigger\",\n    \"Resume Entry\",\n]\n\nSECTION_FIELDS = [\n    \"Goal\",\n    \"Acceptance\",\n    \"Current\",\n    \"Next\",\n    \"Completed\",\n    \"Evidence\",\n    \"Blockers\",\n]\n\nSECTION_SET = set(SECTION_FIELDS)\nMETA_SET = set(META_FIELDS)\n\n\ndef normalize_item(value: str) -> str:\n    text = value.strip()\n    if not text:\n        return \"\"\n    return re.sub(r\"^[-*]\\s+\", \"\", text).strip()\n\n\ndef normalize_items(values: list[str]) -> list[str]:\n    items = [normalize_item(value) for value in values]\n    return [item for item in items if item and item.lower() != \"none\"]\n\n\ndef parse_active_task(path: Path) -> dict[str, object]:\n    text = path.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\")"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport argparse\nimport json\nimport re\nimport sys\nimport tempfile\nfrom datetime import datetime\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nMETA_FIELDS = [\n    \"Status\",\n    \"Priority\",\n    \"Started\",\n    \"Updated\",\n    \"Workspace\",\n    \"Owner\",\n    \"User Trigger\",\n    \"Resume Entry\",\n]\n\nSECTION_FIELDS = [\n    \"Goal\",\n    \"Acceptance\",\n    \"Current\",\n    \"Next\",\n    \"Completed\",\n    \"Evidence\",\n    \"Blockers\",\n]\n\nSECTION_SET = set(SECTION_FIELDS)\nMETA_SET = set(META_FIELDS)\n\n\ndef normalize_item(value: str) -> str:\n    text = value.strip()\n    if not text:\n        return \"\"\n    return re.sub(r\"^[-*]\\s+\", \"\", text).strip()\n\n\ndef normalize_items(values: list[str]) -> list[str]:\n    items = [normalize_item(value) for value in values]\n    return [item for item in items if item and item.lower() != \"none\"]\n\n\ndef parse_active_task(path: Path) -> dict[str, object]:\n    text = path.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\")","cwd":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773932997097}}
{"type":"message","id":"4e7c7a16","parentId":"2b1c8511","timestamp":"2026-03-19T15:10:27.654Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ACTIVE_TASK.md exists and the CLI exists. The issue is about the behavior - after completing one step, the system should automatically continue to the next without waiting for a user message. But looking at the rules in AGENTS.md:\n\n> If context is compacted, the session restarts, or another task interrupts, recover by reading `checklists/ACTIVE_TASK.md` first\n\nThis implies the ACTIVE_TASK is primarily for recovery after interruptions, not for automatic continuation.\n\nThe \"immediately start the next item\" rule is about not asking the user \"要不要继续\", not about automatic execution within the same session.\n\nThe key issue the user is describing: after completing one step, the assistant would stop and not continue to the next. Let me think about what would cause this.\n\n\nI'm realizing the system might be stopping because after a tool result comes back, if I don't explicitly call another tool or yield, the turn ends naturally - so I'm ending my turn without advancing to the next item in the queue. I should explain this to the user and show how `sessions_yield` could be used to hand control back for automatic continuation, then demonstrate how to properly use it in a loop.\n\nBut wait - the user actually did receive a response, which means the session was still running. If I was doing a tool call followed by `sessions_yield`, the system would have waited for the next message before responding. The fact that I replied directly tells me I wasn't using `sessions_yield` to hand off control.\n\nSo the real issue is that I was completing one step but then not automatically triggering the next one - I need to check how the ACTIVE_TASK.md was supposed to be driving the continuation between steps.\n\nThe problem seems to be that after I update the file and complete my response, the session ends, and when the user sends the next message, the system recovers from ACTIVE_TASK.md but that requires a new user message to kick off. The automatic continuation mechanism might not be firing between steps because there's no new message arriving.\n\nI'm realizing there's no automatic heartbeat or scheduled trigger that would pick up the next task - I should suggest adding a cron-based heartbeat that can automatically resume from where we left off.\n\nBut the deeper issue is that the system is clearly waiting for user input between steps. I think the user might have been working through a list where I completed one item and then just... stopped, without prompting for the next one. Let me look at the actual execution history to see what happened. Looking at the execution history, it seems like after completing each layer (1, 2, 3), I was waiting for user input before moving forward rather than automatically continuing to the next step. The same pattern appears in the THS/TDX routing fixes where I'd finish one component and then wait for the user's \"继续修理\" message. I need to update the ACTIVE_TASK.md file to reflect that I'm moving to the next layer, and I should suggest that once a step finishes, I should immediately begin the next one in my response rather than waiting for additional input.","thinkingSignature":"2fd453c0c00c7630a8a41416599b8215f4a98569dcb88484e397ec1bd0e7a1a1"},{"type":"text","text":"客观分析一下问题：\n\n**现象**：完成一个步骤后没自动继续下一个\n\n**根本原因**：Active task 机制是\"恢复铁轨\"（中断后恢复），不是\"自动引擎\"。每步完成后更新了 ACTIVE_TASK.md，但 session turn 结束时如果没有下一条消息进来，系统就停了。\n\n今天的实际执行模式：\n```\n用户发消息 → 我处理 Current → 更新 ACTIVE_TASK → 回复用户 → 等待下一条消息\n                                            ↑\n                                    这里停了，除非有新消息触发\n```\n\n你说得对，我应该**在回复末尾主动继续下一个**，而不是等你下次发消息。\n\n看一下连续任务链里有没有可以自动触发的定时任务：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pwt0r1xtbphi_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw cron list 2>&1 | grep -v \"^\\[plugins\\]\" | grep -v \"^$\" | head -20"}}],"api":"a