{"type":"message","id":"ec685fbf","parentId":"c0d7df21","timestamp":"2026-03-19T15:13:07.079Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the cron job is created. Now let me also think about the other part - the ACTIVE_TASK.md mechanism within the session. The user's specific complaint is that after completing one step, the system doesn't continue to the next. \n\nThe key fix is: after completing a step in my response, I should use `sessions_spawn` to continue the next step, rather than just waiting for the user or a cron job. But that's overkill for most cases.\n\nActually, the simplest and most reliable fix for the \"within-session continuation\" problem is: **update the HEARTBEAT.md to also check ACTIVE_TASK.md**. When the heartbeat fires, it reads ACTIVE_TASK.md. If Status=active and Next has items, it sends a message to the main session to continue.\n\n\nBut heartbeats run in the main session too, so this could create a nested situation. The cron job I just created is isolated and will run separately every 30 minutes, which should handle continuation without blocking the main session. I should wrap up by summarizing the solution and describing how it solves the core problem.","thinkingSignature":"53a058fc23bf021cd6ffce3ebb877ff1eae0ec4b369a51e4b4ae0fbe0a6b7930"},{"type":"text","text":"定时任务创建成功（ID: `b2818217`）。同时再优化一个——把 ACTIVE_TASK 检查集成进现有的心跳：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7ipmjj9370m3_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"ACTIVE_TASK\\|heartbeat.*active\\|active_task\" ~/.openclaw/workspace/HEARTBEAT.md 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":119931,"output":307,"cacheRead":24293,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":144531,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773933169765}}
