{"type":"message","id":"522e2f77","parentId":"be9d4f52","timestamp":"2026-03-19T15:22:36.094Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The script uses `openclaw memory-pro` for two things:\n1. `memory-pro list --scope agent:main --json` - to get existing memory IDs\n2. `memory-pro import <path> --scope agent:main` - to import new memories\n\nBut `memory-pro` doesn't exist. Let me check if there's an alternative way to list/openclaw memory items. Maybe there's a `mcp` command or the memory system works differently.\n\nLooking at the OpenClaw memory system, it seems to use files in `memory/` directory rather than a database. The `openclaw memory` command is for searching/indexing files, not for programmatic list/import.\n \nSo the `memory-pro` plugin that the script relies on isn't actually available in the current OpenClaw setup. The most practical solution would be to rewrite the sync logic to work directly with the memory files in the `memory/` directory instead of trying to use a non-existent plugin command.\n\nLooking at the actual script behavior, it's trying to list existing memory IDs and then import new ones, but since the `memory-pro` command isn't installed, this whole flow is broken. The cleanest fix is to either install the missing `memory-pro` plugin or adapt the script to use the file-based memory system that's actually present.","thinkingSignature":"a3be578db2c60917e38300de6a19e11fdc373015d34f0da2490f796f444820d6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jm6m4qp27x5d_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls ~/.openclaw/skills/ | grep -i memory; ls ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/ | grep -i memory; ls ~/.agents/skills/ 2>/dev/null | grep -i memory"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":118924,"output":331,"cacheRead":24293,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":143548,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":17